Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Metropolitan deer, presumably whitetails, are a very different
population from their wild brethren. As no signs are reported along
with these deaths, other than "convulsions," which could be almost
anything, the question remains open until further necropsy reports
are released. By the numbers reported there will be ample animals for
examination. However, I would point out that until the cause is
better delineated moribund animals should not be put down by shooting
them in the head. It makes brain tissue examinations difficult to say
the least. Any guidance from informed members would be appreciated. - Mod.MHJ

Ashland in Jackson County, Oregon, can be located on the map at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jackson_County_Oregon_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Ashland_Highlighted.svg>
The state, in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States, can
be seen on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?g=5711789&v=42.195,-122.709,5>.

Photos of black-tailed deer can be seen at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black-tailed_Deer>. - CopyEd.MJ]
